				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">Corruption Scandal at Petrobras Threatens Brazil&#8217;s Economy</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Dan Horch			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2015-02-12T01:19:42+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">February 11, 2015 8:19 pm</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">February 11, 2015 8:19 pm</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content">
	<div class="w592"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/02/12/business/12BRAZILDEBT/12BRAZILDEBT-tmagArticle.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/02/12/business/12BRAZILDEBT/12BRAZILDEBT-tmagArticle.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/02/12/business/12BRAZILDEBT/12BRAZILDEBT-tmagArticle.jpg" id="100000003504948" width="592" height="396" alt="A protest against the recent layoffs at Petrobras on Tuesday in Rio de Janeiro. The company is clamping down on spending."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="396"><meta itemprop="width" content="592"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">A protest against the recent layoffs at Petrobras on Tuesday in Rio de Janeiro. The company is clamping down on spending.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Ricardo Moraes/Reuters</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2015/02/11/a-corruption-scandal-at-petrobras-threatens-brazils-bond-market-and-economy/" data-title="Corruption Scandal at Petrobras Threatens Brazil&#8217;s Economy" data-description="Problems caused by a police investigation into bribery accusations at Brazilâs state-controlled petroleum giant Petrobras are putting the capital markets and other companies at risk.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">SÃO PAULO, Brazil â The accusations of corruption at Brazilâs state-controlled petroleum giant Petrobras have already led to a <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/12/08/world/americas/brazil-to-indict-key-figures-in-oil-company-graft-scandal.html">political scandal</a> and a <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/02/07/business/international/new-management-at-petrobras-fails-to-appease-investors.html">change in management</a>. Now, the problems are threatening other Brazilian companies and may even tip the country into recession.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">It would be hard to overstate Petrobrasâs importance in Brazil. It produces more than 90 percent of the countryâs petroleum, owns all of the nationâs refineries, operates more than 21,000 miles of pipelines, dominates wholesale gas and diesel distribution, and even owns the largest chain of service stations.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThe governmentâs plan was to make Petrobras as big as possible,â said Samuel Pessoa, an economist at the FundaÃ§Ã£o Getulio Vargas in Rio de Janeiro. He estimated that the company, through its own operations and its subcontractors, was responsible for about a tenth of Brazilâs economic output.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In the wake of a police investigation, called Operation Car Wash, that indicated that Petrobrasâs suppliers and subcontractors had bribed executives in return for inflated contracts, the company has halted payments on many projects. Petrobras has also prohibited new contracts with some of the countryâs biggest engineering and oil services firms.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The drop in the companyâs spending will probably shave 0.75 percent off growth of the nationâs economy this year, Mr. Pessoa said â enough to tip a sluggish economy into a mild recession.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The companyâs moves are also threatening the bottom lines of subcontractors, which are getting hit twice: Their cash flow has plummeted and the crisis means that they cannot borrow money to tide them over.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Petrobrasâs problems are also spreading to Brazilâs capital markets.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Because of uncertainties over how much the company will have to write down the value of some assets because of corruption, Petrobrasâs auditor, PricewaterhouseCoopers, has refused to sign its quarterly earnings release.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Without an audited earnings release, Petrobras, with net debt of $110 billion, cannot tap the global bond market.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Since Petrobras was seen as the bluest of blue chips, its bonds traditionally served as a benchmark for all Brazilian companies.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Without that benchmark, other companies in Brazil are not even trying to use the bond market.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Local companies sold $37 billion in global bonds last year, according to Dealogic. Since November, when Petrobras failed to produce an audited earnings release, not a single Brazilian corporate bond issue has come to market. January is usually a good month for Brazilian companies to sell bonds. In January 2014, they sold nearly $6.5 billion worth.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âA few companies with strong balance sheets could still sell bonds, but they would pay more than before, so theyâre staying away. There are other companies who really need to raise money right now, and they canât do it,â said Marcel Kussaba, director of equity and debt research at the Brazilian asset manager Quantitas.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">One Petrobras subcontractor, Alumini, has already asked for a bankruptcy courtâs protection, claiming that Petrobras owes it 1.2 billion reais, or $420 million.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">OAS, the countryâs fifth-largest engineering company and a major Petrobras subcontractor, has <a href="//www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-01-10/brazils-oas-said-to-seek-760-million-loan-after-payment-missed">missed bond payments</a> and is trying to negotiate with creditors to avoid bankruptcy. OAS has 7.9 billion reais in debt, or about $2.8 billion, including nearly $1.8 billion in bonds, many held by foreign investors.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The drilling company Sete Brasil is said to be negotiating with state-owned banks to raise $4.5 billion to keep afloat.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But because current or former executives of Sete Brasil, as well as OAS and Alumini, are under investigation on accusations of <a href="//www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-02-05/brazil-federal-police-carry-out-62-court-orders-in-carwash-case">funneling money</a> from inflated contracts to politicians and Petrobras executives, this loan may not be possible.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Sete Brasil owes $4.3 billion to banks. Three banks are also among the companyâs owners, including BTG Pactual, which holds the biggest stake, 27 percent. The companyâs owners have invested an additional $3 billion, but because such investments are often through instruments that contain co-investors, these banksâ exposure may be less.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">If Sete Brasil fails, the companies under contract to build its rigs will also suffer.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Similar problems can be expected throughout the construction and energy sectors as Petrobrasâs subcontractors â many of them giant companies â cut spending, even if they avoid bankruptcy.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âWe are going to see a lot of companies in the sector closing,â said Adriano Pires, director of the Brazilian Center for Infrastructure.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Others will have to sell assets to survive.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âBecause of the Car Wash investigation, there will be specific sectors, particularly in infrastructure, where we will see more M.&amp;A. activity this year,â said Antonio Pereira, Goldman Sachsâs head of investment banking for Brazil.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Airports and highways are likely to be among the assets put up for sale, Mr. Pereira said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Even as investment banks look to profit from advising on mergers and acquisitions, other banks could be hurt.</p>
<div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/02/12/business/12SKYBOX1/12SKYBOX1-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/02/12/business/12SKYBOX1/12SKYBOX1-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/02/12/business/12SKYBOX1/12SKYBOX1-blog480.jpg" id="100000003504934" width="480" height="327" alt="Aldemir Bendine will take the reins at Petrobras. He was formerly the chief executive of the government-controlled Banco do Brasil."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="327"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Aldemir Bendine will take the reins at Petrobras. He was formerly the chief executive of the government-controlled Banco do Brasil.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Nacho Doce/Reuters</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The countryâs largest bank, the government-controlled Banco do Brasil, has 11 percent of its loan portfolio in energy, heavy construction and related sectors, according to a study by the investment bank Brasil Plural. Like Brazilâs other big banks, Banco do Brasil is not considered a bankruptcy risk because it has strong reserves and a diverse income stream, as well as implicit government support. But some smaller banks are vulnerable.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Citing outsize exposure to construction companies by the midsize bank Banco Pine, Moodyâs in January downgraded its debt deeper into junk status and put it under review for additional downgrades.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âI donât expect any banks to go bankrupt as a result of Car Wash,â said JoÃ£o Augusto Salles, financial sector analyst at the Rio de Janeiro investment consultant Lopes Filho, âbut some might have to be sold to bigger ones.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Petrobrasâs first challenge is to calculate how much it must write down the value of its assets because of corruptionso that it can release an audited balance sheet. If the company fails to do so by June, owners of its $54.5 billion in bonds could demand immediate repayment.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Most analysts said that situation was unlikely, and even if it did occur, it might not mean that the company would default on its bonds. If any company in Brazil is too big to fail, itâs Petrobras.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âWe think the government would step in or push local banks to provide the necessary financing,â said Brigitte Posch, head of emerging market corporate debt at Babson Capital, which owns Petrobras bonds. âThis company is just too important to Brazil.â</p>
<div id="addendums" class="addendums"><div class="story-addendum theme-correction"><strong>Correction: February 12, 2015</strong> <br>An earlier version of a picture caption with this article gave outdated information. The person shown, Aldemir Bendine, is the newly appointed chief of Petrobras, not chief executive of Banco do Brasil, a post he gave up to take the top job at Petrobras.</div><div class="story-addendum theme-correction"><strong>Correction: February 13, 2015</strong> <br>An article on Thursday about the repercussions to the Brazilian economy of a corruption scandal involving the state-owned petroleum giant Petrobras misidentified a target of the continuing investigation. Former executives of the drilling company Sete Brasil are under scrutiny, not the company itself.</div></div><footer class="story-footer">
